### Study documents

::: {.cell}
::: {.cell-output-display}
```{=html}
<div class="datatables html-widget html-fill-item-overflow-hidden html-fill-item" id="htmlwidget-9d79e62b65fb576cfc12" style="width:100%;height:auto;"></div>
<script type="application/json" data-for="htmlwidget-9d79e62b65fb576cfc12">{"x":{"filter":"none","vertical":false,"data":[["Creation of study protocol & funding proposal                      ","Creation of study protocol & funding proposal                      ","Creation of study protocol & funding proposal                      ","Creation of study protocol & funding proposal                      ","Creation of study protocol & funding proposal                      ","Creation of informed consent process and informed consentform (ICF)","Creation of questionnaires and other study tools                   ","Creation of questionnaires and other study tools                   "],["One PPI representative co-creates or reviews          ","A group of PPI representatives co-create or review    ","A group of PPI representatives co-create or review    ","A group of PPI representatives co-create or review    ","PPI representatives provide a formal letter of support","Reviewing by crowdsourcing                            ","A group of PPI representatives co-create and review   ","A group of PPI representatives co-create and review   "],["A Protocol Advisor was involved. The Protocol Advisor, living with HIV and part of the military HIV programme, made suggestions and recommendations based on personal experiences and knowledge. He provided important feedback from the perspective of the patient with issues specific and not-so-specific to the military, issues regarding confidentiality, sexuality, drug and alcohol use, and the difference between military duties and responsibilities throughout the protocol stages.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 ","On average, each site’s Community Advisory Board consisted of 13–19 stakeholders, including leaders of HIV/AIDS-related Community-based Organisations, hospital-based HIV/AIDS service providers, and HIV/AIDS network leaders in minority communities. CABs meet once a month at the research site or in the agencies or community organizations represented by the CAB members. The meetings are conducted by the project director and research staff. The CAB reviewed the study protocol and made suggestions regarding the language used in the protocols to avoid stigmatizing the community. For example, the CAB recommended that the study protocol should specify that the study is not only about reducing HIV risks but also about improving healthy relationships among black couples and about learning strategies for a healthy lifestyle.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        ","Working group members facilitated workshops with youth to train them in research methods and collaboratively designed the protocol. In all, 27 youth participated in an iterative protocol planning process.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     ","Consultation in the format of focus group discussions to inform the design of a clinical trial to reduce postnatal transmission of HIV. Participants: HIV-positive mothers. Mothers consulted raised concerns about the amount of blood that was planned to be taken from mothers and their babies as detailed in the draft protocol. The mothers were asked to consider what would be an acceptable amount of blood to be taken for the purpose of the research. After the consultation, the protocol was amended to reduce the quantity of blood to be taken to a level that was acceptable to mothers but still adequate for laboratory analyses. Before data collection, the interviewers participated in a 2-week training course. Question guides were translated into the local language, Chichewa, and back-translated into English. All interviews and focus group discussions were audio-taped, simultaneously transcribed and translated verbatim into English by the interviewer directly after the interviews and focus group discussions were conducted, and then subsequently reviewed by investigators.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          ","PPI representatives wrote a letter of support for a project funding                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              ","Community feedback on the informed consent process was collected by transforming the 20-page informed consent form into a series of interactive, plain-language, animated video modules, which were screened at an open public discussion. The modules were created by a local community-based organization that specializes in translating clinical science to lay audiences through creative products. The event was advertised via Facebook (295 followers) and Twitter (329 followers) accounts of our research group. We also distributed physical copies of the event flyers at both a local infectious disease clinic and a clinical research center. We additionally sent the event information to local HIV community engagement advocates. Importantly, we solicited the assistance of a community member known to our research group as a highly engaged local HIV advocate who had previously participated in crowdsourcing research conducted by our group.\r\nAfter screening, the participants discussed which parts of the informed consent modules were easiest and most difficult to understand, what additional information they thought a trial participant should know (i.e. what was missing from the modules), and what additional formats would be useful for conveying informed consent information to potential trial participants. This discussion was guided by a facilitator. To obtain a sufficient participation to benefit from multiple perspectives, we offered attendance incentives of a $15 gift card per attendee and also provided lunch. Ultimately a total of 20 people participated in-person at the event. We collected 1h of audio-recorded feedback.","We reviewed a new PROUD study questionnaire by email with 6 community members and 6 participants                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                 ","Researchers worked with several young people (mostly from community facilities) to test interviews, improve the design of study materials and develop a video explaining the study to potential participants                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     "],["<a href='https://tinyurl.com/Carey1992'>Carey 1992<\/a>    ","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/MottCAB2008'>Mott 2008<\/a>   ","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/Flicker2008'>Flicker 2006<\/a>","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/Boote2010'>Boote 2010<\/a>    ","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/Lessard2019'>Lessard 2019<\/a>","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/DaySuz2020'>Day 2020<\/a>     ","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/Gafos2020'>Gafos 2020<\/a>    ","<a href='https://tinyurl.com/South2016'>South 2016<\/a>    "]],"container":"<table class=\"display\">\n  <thead>\n    <tr>\n      <th>Task<\/th>\n      <th>Strategy<\/th>\n      <th>Example for Strategy<\/th>\n      <th>Link<\/th>\n    <\/tr>\n  <\/thead>\n<\/table>","options":{"dom":"t","initComplete":"function(settings, json) {\n$(this.api().table().header()).css({'font-size': '13px'});\n$(this.api().table().body()).css({'font-size': '12px'});\n}","columnDefs":[{"name":"Task","targets":0},{"name":"Strategy","targets":1},{"name":"Example for Strategy","targets":2},{"name":"Link","targets":3}],"order":[],"autoWidth":false,"orderClasses":false}},"evals":["options.initComplete"],"jsHooks":[]}</script>
```
